        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9788437605227" href="/book/show/1256231.El_rbol_de_la_ciencia">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/43695560-dennis?shelf=owned-and-read">owned-and-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/43695560-dennis?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/43695560-dennis?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/43695560-dennis?shelf=spanish-literature">spanish-literature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/43695560-dennis?shelf=novels">novels</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2636863634" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer653752319161253766">ENGLISH REVIEW:<br/><br/>This is the first novel I have read by Pío Baroja and I found it excellently narrated. It tells the life of Andrés Hurtado, a young man who begins to study Medicine. In the first part of the book we are told about his environment, his family, his university colleagues and his interests. Towards the middle of the book there is a part that is a philosophical debate between the protagonist and his uncle Iturrioz, a very interesting conversation that despite not reaching any resolutio</span>
  <span id="freeText653752319161253766" style="display:none">ENGLISH REVIEW:<br /><br />This is the first novel I have read by Pío Baroja and I found it excellently narrated. It tells the life of Andrés Hurtado, a young man who begins to study Medicine. In the first part of the book we are told about his environment, his family, his university colleagues and his interests. Towards the middle of the book there is a part that is a philosophical debate between the protagonist and his uncle Iturrioz, a very interesting conversation that despite not reaching any resolution, serves to highlight the thoughts of both protagonists, which will influence the rest of the plot. Later, after finishing his Medicine studies, Andrés goes to work in a town called Alcolea, and after returning to Madrid he continues his life with his old friend Lulú. The end of the novel is somewhat bitter, but serves as closure to the life of Andrés. The novel is characterized by bitterness, existentialism, uncertainty and melancholy. <br /><br />REVIEW EN ESPAÑOL:<br /><br />Es la primera novela que leo de Pío Baroja y me ha parecido excelentemente narrada. Relata la vida de Andrés Hurtado, un joven que comienza a estudiar medicina. En la primera parte del libro nos habla de su entorno, su familia, sus compañeros de universidad y sus inquietudes. Hacia la mitad del libro hay una parte que es un debate filosófico entre el protagonista y su tío Iturrioz, debate muy interesante que pese a no llegar a ninguna solución, sirve para poner en primer plano los pensamientos de ambos protagonistas, los cuales marcarán el resto de la trama. Más tarde, tras terminar la carrera de Medicina, Andrés va a trabajar a un pueblo llamado Alcolea, y tras volver a Madrid continúa su vida con su antigua amiga Lulú. El final de la novela es algo amargo, pero sirve de cierre a la vida de Andrés. Novela caracterizada por la amargura, el existencialismo, la incertidumbre y la melancolía. </span>
  <a data-text-id="653752319161253766" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


