        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer584916432" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13642394157513214331">I really enjoyed the book, it was kind of depressing tough. My first touch with this book was back when I was 15, and I&apos;d just finished an existentialist novel from Carmen Laforet called Nada (which I really enjoyed). I remember how in love I was with those first pages, maybe because It was quite how I felt about my surroundings but then I left it (I wasn&apos;t quite ready for the philosophical views, I guess)... until years later when I had to (re-)read it for school. <br/><br/>&apos;Fuera de aquellos momentos, e</span>
  <span id="freeText13642394157513214331" style="display:none">I really enjoyed the book, it was kind of depressing tough. My first touch with this book was back when I was 15, and I'd just finished an existentialist novel from Carmen Laforet called Nada (which I really enjoyed). I remember how in love I was with those first pages, maybe because It was quite how I felt about my surroundings but then I left it (I wasn't quite ready for the philosophical views, I guess)... until years later when I had to (re-)read it for school. <br /><br />'Fuera de aquellos momentos, en los demás, el estudio, las discusiones, la casa, los amigos, sus correrías, todo esto, mezclado con sus pensamientos, le daba una impresión de dolor, de amargura en el espíritu. La vida en general, y sobre todo la suya, le parecía una cosa fea, turbia, dolorosa e indomable.'<br /><br />I think Pío Baroja did a masterpiece making a critique of the spanish society of back then, their hypocrisy to the turn of events when Spain lost Cuba and Philippines (disaster of '98), the lack of support to science, ... all this through its main character Andrés Hurtado and it's life experiences. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13642394157513214331" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


