<div id="review_114419959" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/114419959" />
    <a title="Ann Johnson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4062888-ann-johnson"><img alt="Ann Johnson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1291404243p2/4062888.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/114419959?book_show_action=true">Jul 30, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ann Johnson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ann Johnson" href="/user/show/4062888-ann-johnson">Ann Johnson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer114419959" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1217247322648017816">For being written a century ago, this was surprisingly easy to get through. I liked reading about what medical school and physicians&apos; practices were like back then. (&quot;Have you ever heard of these things called GERMS?&quot;) I enjoyed the book, but I don&apos;t think I&apos;d recommend it unless someone wants to spend 300 pages reading about the futility of life and the impossibility of positive change. And the final chapter is a pretty depressing buzz-kill. </span>
  <span id="freeText1217247322648017816" style="display:none">For being written a century ago, this was surprisingly easy to get through. I liked reading about what medical school and physicians' practices were like back then. ("Have you ever heard of these things called GERMS?") I enjoyed the book, but I don't think I'd recommend it unless someone wants to spend 300 pages reading about the futility of life and the impossibility of positive change. And the final chapter is a pretty depressing buzz-kill. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1217247322648017816" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


